---
import Layout from "@/layouts/Layout.astro";
import SiteHeader from "@/components/SiteHeader.astro";
import SiteFooter from "@/components/SiteFooter.astro";
import { GITHUB_REPO } from "@/lib/site";
---

<Layout
  title="Cloudflare Tunnel — LetsChat Self-Hosting"
  description="Put your LetsChat server online through a Cloudflare Tunnel — no open inbound ports except the two needed for voice. Plain-English, step-by-step."
>
  <SiteHeader active="self-hosting" />

  <main class="relative max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6 py-16 space-y-8 overflow-hidden">
    <div class="hero-glow hero-glow-a"></div>

    <div class="relative z-10 space-y-3">
      <nav class="flex items-center gap-2 text-xs text-muted-foreground">
        <a href="/self-hosting" class="hover:text-foreground transition-colors">Self-Hosting</a>
        <span>/</span>
        <span class="text-foreground">Cloudflare Tunnel</span>
      </nav>
      <h1 class="text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-semibold tracking-tight">Cloudflare Tunnel</h1>
      <p class="text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed pt-1">
        Put your home server online through Cloudflare without opening any inbound ports —
        except the two that voice/video physically needs. This is the easiest path if your
        domain is on Cloudflare. Allow ~20 minutes.
      </p>
    </div>

    <!-- ── Concept ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
    <section class="space-y-6">
      <article class="step-card rounded-xl p-6 space-y-3">
        <h2 class="text-xl font-medium">First, what a tunnel actually is</h2>
        <p class="text-sm text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed">
          LetsChat runs as a handful of services on your server, but they're only reachable on
          your home network. The old way to expose them is to open ports <code class="text-xs">80</code>/<code class="text-xs">443</code>
          on your router and point your domain at your home IP — which publishes your address and
          opens your machine to the whole internet.
        </p>
        <p class="text-sm text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed">
          A Cloudflare Tunnel flips that around. A small program — <code class="text-xs">cloudflared</code> —
          runs next to LetsChat and makes <strong>one outbound connection up to Cloudflare</strong>, then holds it
          open. When someone visits <code class="text-xs">chat.yourdomain.com</code>, the request arrives at Cloudflare
          and is piped <span class="italic">back down that connection</span> to your server. You never open an inbound
          port, your home IP is never published, and Cloudflare gives you HTTPS for free.
        </p>
        <p class="text-sm text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed">
          You'll point five subdomains at five services through that tunnel:
        </p>
        <ul class="list-disc pl-5 text-sm text-muted-foreground space-y-1">
          <li><code class="text-xs">auth</code> — login &amp; tokens &nbsp;·&nbsp; <code class="text-xs">connect</code> — first-run discovery</li>
          <li><code class="text-xs">chat</code> — realtime database &nbsp;·&nbsp; <code class="text-xs">files</code> — uploads &nbsp;·&nbsp; <code class="text-xs">lk</code> — voice signalling</li>
        </ul>
        <p class="text-sm text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed">
          <strong>The one exception:</strong> the live voice/video audio itself is real-time UDP and
          <strong>cannot</strong> travel through the tunnel. That single kind of traffic reaches your server
          directly, on two ports you forward on your router (Step 7). Skip that and text chat works
          perfectly — voice calls just connect with no sound.
        </p>
      </article>

      <!-- ── The plan ──────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
      <article class="step-card rounded-xl p-6 space-y-3">
        <h2 class="text-xl font-medium">The plan</h2>
        <ol class="list-decimal pl-5 text-sm text-muted-foreground space-y-1">
          <li>Create a tunnel and copy its token</li>
          <li>Download the files</li>
          <li>Fill in your <code class="text-xs">.env</code></li>
          <li>Set the LiveKit secret</li>
          <li>Map the five subdomains</li>
          <li>Start the stack</li>
          <li>Forward the two voice ports</li>
          <li>Open the app</li>
        </ol>
      </article>

      <!-- ── Prerequisites ─────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
      <article class="step-card rounded-xl p-6 space-y-3">
        <h2 class="text-xl font-medium">Before you start</h2>
        <ul class="list-disc pl-5 text-sm text-muted-foreground space-y-1">
          <li>A domain whose DNS is managed by Cloudflare (free plan is fine).</li>
          <li>Cloudflare <strong>Zero Trust</strong> enabled on your account (free).</li>
          <li>An Ubuntu server with Docker Engine + the Compose plugin.</li>
          <li>Admin access to your home router (for the two voice ports in Step 7).</li>
        </ul>
        <p class="text-sm text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed pt-1">
          <strong>30-second voice check.</strong> Voice needs a real public IP. Run this on the server and
          compare the result to the WAN / Internet IP shown on your router's status page:
        </p>
        <pre class="rounded-lg border border-border bg-background p-4 overflow-x-auto text-xs"><code>{`curl -4 ifconfig.me`}</code></pre>
        <p class="text-sm text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed">
          <strong>Same IP</strong> → you're good. <strong>Different</strong> → your ISP puts you behind CGNAT; text chat
          and everything else still works, but voice will need a relay (see <a href="#cgnat" class="underline hover:text-foreground">Voice behind CGNAT</a> at the end).
        </p>
      </article>

      <!-- ── Step 1 ────────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
      <article class="step-card rounded-xl p-6 space-y-3">
        <div class="flex items-center gap-3"><span class="step-num">1</span><h2 class="text-xl font-medium">Create the tunnel &amp; copy the token</h2></div>
        <p class="text-sm text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed">
          In the Cloudflare dashboard: <strong>Zero Trust → Networks → Tunnels → Create a tunnel →
          Cloudflared</strong>. Name it (e.g. <code class="text-xs">letschat</code>) and save.
        </p>
        <p class="text-sm text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed">
          The next screen shows an install command containing <code class="text-xs">--token &lt;LONG-STRING&gt;</code>.
          <strong>Copy that token</strong> — it's the connector's password and the only thing you need from this page.
          Leave the tab open; you'll add the subdomains in Step 5.
        </p>
        <p class="text-xs text-muted-foreground">
          Already run <code class="text-xs">cloudflared</code> on this server for other apps? Don't create a second
          connector — skip to <a href="#existing" class="underline hover:text-foreground">Already running cloudflared</a> at the bottom.
        </p>
      </article>

      <!-- ── Step 2 ────────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
      <article class="step-card rounded-xl p-6 space-y-3">
        <div class="flex items-center gap-3"><span class="step-num">2</span><h2 class="text-xl font-medium">Download the files</h2></div>
        <p class="text-sm text-muted-foreground">On the server, in a fresh folder:</p>
        <pre class="rounded-lg border border-border bg-background p-4 overflow-x-auto text-xs"><code>{`mkdir letschat && cd letschat

# the stack + the cloudflared connector overlay
wget https://raw.githubusercontent.com/${GITHUB_REPO}/main/docker-compose.prod.base.yml
wget https://raw.githubusercontent.com/${GITHUB_REPO}/main/docker-compose.prod.tunnel.yml

# the LiveKit config
mkdir livekit
wget -O livekit/config.prod.yaml \\
  https://raw.githubusercontent.com/${GITHUB_REPO}/main/livekit/config.prod.yaml

# your settings file
wget -O .env \\
  https://raw.githubusercontent.com/${GITHUB_REPO}/main/.env.production.tunnel.example`}</code></pre>
        <p class="text-xs text-muted-foreground">All images are pre-built — no Rust/Node toolchains needed on the server.</p>
      </article>

      <!-- ── Step 3 ────────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
      <article class="step-card rounded-xl p-6 space-y-3">
        <div class="flex items-center gap-3"><span class="step-num">3</span><h2 class="text-xl font-medium">Fill in your <code class="text-base">.env</code></h2></div>
        <p class="text-sm text-muted-foreground">Generate the secrets first:</p>
        <pre class="rounded-lg border border-border bg-background p-4 overflow-x-auto text-xs"><code>{`openssl rand -hex 32      # AUTH_JWT_SECRET, POSTGRES_PASSWORD, MINIO_SECRET_KEY
openssl rand -base64 32   # LIVEKIT_API_SECRET`}</code></pre>
        <p class="text-sm text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed">
          Open <code class="text-xs">.env</code> and set <strong>every field in this block</strong> — the stack won't start
          without <code class="text-xs">POSTGRES_PASSWORD</code>, and you can't sign in without the admin account.
          Replace <code class="text-xs">example.com</code> with your domain throughout:
        </p>
        <pre class="rounded-lg border border-border bg-background p-4 overflow-x-auto text-xs"><code>{`# Secrets
AUTH_JWT_SECRET=            # openssl rand -hex 32
POSTGRES_PASSWORD=         # openssl rand -hex 32
LIVEKIT_API_SECRET=        # openssl rand -base64 32
MINIO_ACCESS_KEY=          # any username you choose, e.g. letschat-minio
MINIO_SECRET_KEY=          # openssl rand -hex 32
CLOUDFLARE_TUNNEL_TOKEN=   # the token you copied in Step 1

# First admin account (created on first start — change the password after)
ADMIN_BOOTSTRAP_USERNAME=admin
ADMIN_BOOTSTRAP_PASSWORD=  # a strong password
ADMIN_BOOTSTRAP_EMAIL=you@example.com

# Your public URLs
MINIO_PUBLIC_ENDPOINT=https://files.example.com
DISCOVERY_SPACETIMEDB_URI=wss://chat.example.com
DISCOVERY_AUTH_URL=https://auth.example.com
DISCOVERY_LIVEKIT_URL=wss://lk.example.com`}</code></pre>
        <p class="text-sm text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed">
          <strong>Email.</strong> By default LetsChat sends confirmation emails, so it needs SMTP. Using a Gmail
          account? Enable 2-Step Verification, create an <strong>App Password</strong> (Google Account → Security →
          App passwords — a 16-char code, <span class="italic">not</span> your normal password), and set:
        </p>
        <pre class="rounded-lg border border-border bg-background p-4 overflow-x-auto text-xs"><code>{`SMTP_HOST=smtp.gmail.com
SMTP_PORT=587
SMTP_USER=you@gmail.com
SMTP_PASSWORD=         # the 16-char App Password
EMAIL_FROM_ADDRESS=you@gmail.com`}</code></pre>
        <p class="text-sm text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed">
          <strong>No email yet?</strong> Set <code class="text-xs">REQUIRE_EMAIL_CONFIRMATION=false</code> and
          <code class="text-xs">EMAIL_SENDER=log</code> — accounts then work without SMTP.
        </p>
        <p class="text-xs text-muted-foreground">
          Everything else in the file has a working default and is documented inline — leave it alone unless
          you have a reason. (One to know about: <code class="text-xs">SPACETIMEDB_SERVICE_TOKEN</code> is optional;
          blank is fine — it only makes one admin-panel card editable.)
        </p>
      </article>

      <!-- ── Step 4 ────────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
      <article class="step-card rounded-xl p-6 space-y-3">
        <div class="flex items-center gap-3"><span class="step-num">4</span><h2 class="text-xl font-medium">Set the LiveKit secret</h2></div>
        <p class="text-sm text-muted-foreground">Open <code class="text-xs">livekit/config.prod.yaml</code> and paste the same secret you put in <code class="text-xs">.env</code>:</p>
        <pre class="rounded-lg border border-border bg-background p-4 overflow-x-auto text-xs"><code>{`keys:
  letschat-prod: <paste LIVEKIT_API_SECRET here>`}</code></pre>
        <p class="text-xs text-muted-foreground">Leave the rest of the file (ports, <code class="text-xs">use_external_ip: true</code>) as-is.</p>
      </article>

      <!-- ── Step 5 ────────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
      <article class="step-card rounded-xl p-6 space-y-3">
        <div class="flex items-center gap-3"><span class="step-num">5</span><h2 class="text-xl font-medium">Map the five subdomains</h2></div>
        <p class="text-sm text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed">
          Back on your tunnel's page, open <strong>Public Hostnames</strong> and add one entry per subdomain.
          The connector runs <span class="italic">inside Docker</span> next to the services, so the targets are the internal
          service names (not <code class="text-xs">localhost</code>):
        </p>
        <pre class="rounded-lg border border-border bg-background p-4 overflow-x-auto text-xs"><code>{`auth.example.com     ->  http://core-api:8787
connect.example.com  ->  http://core-api:8787
chat.example.com     ->  http://spacetimedb:3000     # enable WebSocket
files.example.com    ->  http://minio:44390
lk.example.com       ->  http://livekit:44380        # enable WebSocket`}</code></pre>
        <p class="text-xs text-muted-foreground">
          For <code class="text-xs">chat</code> and <code class="text-xs">lk</code>, turn on <strong>Additional settings → enable WebSocket</strong>.
          Cloudflare creates the DNS records for you automatically.
        </p>
      </article>

      <!-- ── Step 6 ────────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
      <article class="step-card rounded-xl p-6 space-y-3">
        <div class="flex items-center gap-3"><span class="step-num">6</span><h2 class="text-xl font-medium">Start the stack</h2></div>
        <pre class="rounded-lg border border-border bg-background p-4 overflow-x-auto text-xs"><code>{`docker compose -f docker-compose.prod.base.yml -f docker-compose.prod.tunnel.yml up -d`}</code></pre>
        <p class="text-sm text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed">
          The <code class="text-xs">module-init</code> container publishes the SpacetimeDB schema automatically once the
          database is healthy — no manual <code class="text-xs">spacetime publish</code>. Watch it finish with:
        </p>
        <pre class="rounded-lg border border-border bg-background p-4 overflow-x-auto text-xs"><code>{`docker logs -f letschat-module-init`}</code></pre>
      </article>

      <!-- ── Step 7 ────────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
      <article class="step-card rounded-xl p-6 space-y-3">
        <div class="flex items-center gap-3"><span class="step-num">7</span><h2 class="text-xl font-medium">Forward the two voice ports</h2></div>
        <p class="text-sm text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed">
          This is the one step the tunnel can't do — voice media must reach your server directly.
          First find the server's LAN IP and give it a <strong>static DHCP reservation</strong> in your router so it
          never changes:
        </p>
        <pre class="rounded-lg border border-border bg-background p-4 overflow-x-auto text-xs"><code>{`ip -4 -o addr show scope global | awk '{print $2, $4}'   # e.g. eth0 192.168.1.50/24`}</code></pre>
        <p class="text-sm text-muted-foreground">Then, in your router's <span class="italic">Port Forwarding</span> section, forward both of these to that LAN IP:</p>
        <ul class="list-disc pl-5 text-sm text-muted-foreground space-y-1">
          <li><code class="text-xs">44382/udp</code> — the voice/video media (almost every call uses only this)</li>
          <li><code class="text-xs">44381/tcp</code> — fallback for callers on networks that block UDP</li>
        </ul>
        <p class="text-xs text-muted-foreground">
          Don't forward <code class="text-xs">44380</code> — that's signalling, and it already goes through the tunnel.
          A dynamic public IP is fine; only an IP change mid-call needs a LiveKit restart to recover.
        </p>
      </article>

      <!-- ── Step 8 ────────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
      <article class="step-card rounded-xl p-6 space-y-3">
        <div class="flex items-center gap-3"><span class="step-num">8</span><h2 class="text-xl font-medium">Open the app</h2></div>
        <p class="text-sm text-muted-foreground">Confirm the public endpoints answer (from anywhere):</p>
        <pre class="rounded-lg border border-border bg-background p-4 overflow-x-auto text-xs"><code>{`curl -i https://auth.example.com/health
curl -i https://connect.example.com/.well-known/letschat.json`}</code></pre>
        <p class="text-sm text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed">
          In the LetsChat desktop app, enter <code class="text-xs">connect.example.com</code> as the server — it auto-discovers
          the rest. Sign in with the admin account from Step 3, then make a test voice call between two clients.
        </p>
        <p class="text-xs text-muted-foreground">
          Call connects but no audio? The Step 7 ports aren't reaching the host — recheck the forwards and the
          voice check from "Before you start".
        </p>
      </article>

      <!-- ── Alternative: existing connector ───────────────────────────── -->
      <article id="existing" class="step-card alt-card rounded-xl p-6 space-y-3 scroll-mt-24">
        <p class="text-xs font-medium uppercase tracking-wide" style="color: var(--accent-blue)">Alternative setup</p>
        <h2 class="text-xl font-medium">Already running cloudflared (or nginx/Caddy) on this host?</h2>
        <p class="text-sm text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed">
          If you already run a connector natively on the server for other apps, don't run a second one and don't
          use the bundled overlay. Two changes to the path above:
        </p>
        <ul class="list-disc pl-5 text-sm text-muted-foreground space-y-1">
          <li><strong>Step 1 &amp; 6:</strong> skip the bundled connector. Start with the base file only —
            <code class="text-xs">docker compose -f docker-compose.prod.base.yml up -d</code> — and in Step 2 you don't need
            <code class="text-xs">docker-compose.prod.tunnel.yml</code>. Leave <code class="text-xs">CLOUDFLARE_TUNNEL_TOKEN</code> blank;
            your existing connector has its own credentials.</li>
          <li><strong>Step 5:</strong> add the hostnames to your <span class="italic">existing</span> tunnel, pointing at the host's
            <code class="text-xs">localhost</code> ports instead of Docker names:</li>
        </ul>
        <pre class="rounded-lg border border-border bg-background p-4 overflow-x-auto text-xs"><code>{`auth.example.com     ->  http://localhost:8787
connect.example.com  ->  http://localhost:8787
chat.example.com     ->  http://localhost:44300     # enable WebSocket
files.example.com    ->  http://localhost:44390
lk.example.com       ->  http://localhost:44380     # enable WebSocket`}</code></pre>
        <p class="text-xs text-muted-foreground">
          Everything else (the <code class="text-xs">.env</code>, LiveKit secret, voice-port forwarding) is identical.
          Same idea for nginx / Caddy / Traefik on the host — terminate TLS there and proxy to those
          <code class="text-xs">localhost</code> ports, keeping <code class="text-xs">chat</code> and <code class="text-xs">lk</code> as WebSocket upgrades.
        </p>
      </article>

      <!-- ── CGNAT note ────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
      <article id="cgnat" class="step-card alt-card rounded-xl p-6 space-y-3 scroll-mt-24">
        <p class="text-xs font-medium uppercase tracking-wide" style="color: var(--accent-blue)">If the voice check failed</p>
        <h2 class="text-xl font-medium">Voice behind CGNAT</h2>
        <p class="text-sm text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed">
          If your public IP and your router's WAN IP <strong>differ</strong>, your ISP has you behind carrier-grade NAT —
          port forwarding can't reach you, so voice won't work directly (text, chat and files are unaffected). The
          fix is a <strong>TURN relay</strong> both sides connect outbound to:
        </p>
        <ul class="list-disc pl-5 text-sm text-muted-foreground space-y-1">
          <li><strong>TURN on a cheap public-IP VPS</strong> — relays media through a box with a stable, routable IP. All call media flows through it, so size its bandwidth accordingly.</li>
          <li><strong>Cloudflare Realtime (TURN)</strong> — a managed relay at Cloudflare's edge, billed per GB.</li>
        </ul>
      </article>

    </section>

    <div class="flex items-center justify-between pt-4 border-t border-border text-sm">
      <a href="/self-hosting" class="text-muted-foreground hover:text-foreground transition-colors">← Back to overview</a>
      <a href="/self-hosting/caddy" class="text-muted-foreground hover:text-foreground transition-colors">Prefer Caddy? →</a>
    </div>
  </main>
  <SiteFooter />
</Layout>

<style>
  .hero-glow {
    position: absolute;
    pointer-events: none;
    border-radius: 9999px;
    filter: blur(56px);
    opacity: 0.22;
  }

  .hero-glow-a {
    width: 360px;
    height: 260px;
    top: -80px;
    left: -80px;
    background: radial-gradient(circle at 40% 40%, color-mix(in oklch, var(--accent-blue) 80%, white 20%), transparent 70%);
    animation: drift 12s ease-in-out infinite;
  }

  .step-card {
    border: 1px solid oklch(1 0 0 / 0.12);
    background:
      linear-gradient(180deg, oklch(0.22 0 0 / 0.82), oklch(0.185 0 0 / 0.8)),
      linear-gradient(90deg, oklch(0.49 0.23 264.3 / 0.2) 0 4px, transparent 4px 100%);
    box-shadow: 0 14px 34px oklch(0 0 0 / 0.2);
  }

  /* Alternative / aside cards: warmer accent stripe so they read as off-path. */
  .alt-card {
    background:
      linear-gradient(180deg, oklch(0.21 0 0 / 0.82), oklch(0.175 0 0 / 0.8)),
      linear-gradient(90deg, oklch(0.7 0.16 200 / 0.28) 0 4px, transparent 4px 100%);
  }

  .step-num {
    display: inline-flex;
    align-items: center;
    justify-content: center;
    width: 1.75rem;
    height: 1.75rem;
    flex: none;
    border-radius: 9999px;
    background: oklch(0.49 0.23 264.3 / 0.28);
    border: 1px solid oklch(0.62 0.2 264.3 / 0.55);
    color: white;
    font-size: 0.82rem;
    font-weight: 600;
  }

  @keyframes drift {
    0% { transform: translate3d(0, 0, 0) scale(1); }
    50% { transform: translate3d(8px, -12px, 0) scale(1.04); }
    100% { transform: translate3d(0, 0, 0) scale(1); }
  }
</style>
